body:
About that Captain Marvel scene…

There are a lot of good arguments for why this whole discussion is unnecessary.

1. It’s a movie. Real-life-morals usually don’t count here. Especially in action movies like the Marvel Movies.

2. Even if you want to use them here, I don’t see why anyone should feel enough empathy for this douchbag to actually start a huge discussion about it (unless they feel attacked themselves?)

3. A lot of guys say: “But she broke the law even though he didn’t. He was just behaving bad”. And after being told that other heroes do that too, they say that one has to decide if the act of the hero was justified or not. Oh really? And as a man who probably didn’t have that kind of experience in his whole life, while a lot of women have to go through that daily, you feel in the right position to decide what is justified or not?

Well, wouldn’t be the first time.

3. Civil War was about how the Avengers kill innocent people while fighting. The Hulk probably crashed hundreds of cars and houses and other stuff of people who did nothing wrong. That was literally the topic of the movie. Is the distruction they do justified? Of course you can say that Carol didn’t need the motorcycle to save people directly, but she also were on a mission.

(By the way, using that she threatened him as an argument is just hilarious to me, because guess how uncomfortable women feel when men say shit like that. It’s not just the words it’s also the thoughts about what could follow.)

BUT the really important thing is: in that Scene Carol was still without her memories. Basically all she knew she learned from…? Right a dude (or the kree in general). So, saying Carol acted completly intolerable, even though at this point of the movie she acted on the behaviour they teached her, (but also saying Bucky is innocent because he was brainwashed) makes you a hypocrite.

Also that makes every argument against her behavior irrelevant, since she obviously evolved in the movie and no one could proof that she would act like that again.

Still thought the scene was funny.
